@lizziematusov Lastly -- try and find a way to ski for like 10 days straight. I have helped maybe 5-6 novice adults really improve and nothing beats being able to ski for like 10 straight days. 2 or 3 days here or there makes it hard to really improve. 10 days sets you up for a long time.

@lizziematusov Also, master the hockey stop. Being able to stop very fast (/ with your edges) is a huge relief for uncertain terrain. Once mastered, learning how to turn in place on a steep (aka crappy jump turn) gives you the confidence to know you can reposition yourself if needed. Also helps

@lizziematusov Doing the same runs (solid blues) over and over helps a ton. Vary how you take the run, but do the same run. Get super comfortable and just keep changing it up / speeding up. That helps build confidence for new terrain and situations.
